        <abstract> 
<p>DO’s observations on polymorphism in <hi rend="italic">Primula</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Campanula</hi>. CD recognises three classes of dimorphism, as in <hi rend="italic">Primula</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Thymus</hi>, and <hi rend="italic">Campanula</hi> and violets.</p>  
<p>DO’s <hi rend="italic">Campanula</hi> paper and Royal Institution lecture [<hi rend="italic">Not. Proc. R. Inst. G. B.</hi> 3 (1858–62): 431–3].</p> 
            <p>CD’s interest in Fumariaceae from A. Gray’s comments on "selfing".</p>
            <p>Bees bite holes in flowers when same species grows in high density.</p>
            <p>Organisation of CD’s notes.</p>
        </abstract>
